    <h3>Lean</h3>
    <p>Lean project management focuses on maximizing value while minimizing waste through continuous improvement and efficiency. Originally developed in manufacturing, “lean” emphasizes delivering only what customers truly value by eliminating non-essential activities, reducing work in progress, and streamlining workflows. Lean includes identifying value from the customer's perspective, mapping value streams, creating flow, establishing pull-based systems, and pursuing excellence through iteration. By implementing lean practices, organizations can reduce costs, improve quality, shorten delivery times, and enhance customer satisfaction.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>Portfolio Management</h3>
    <p>When organizations oversee multiple interconnected projects simultaneously, “project management” naturally evolves into “portfolio management.” While project managers focus on individual project success, portfolio management takes a higher-level view by selecting, prioritizing, and balancing projects based on organizational goals, resource constraints, and risk tolerance. This evolution requires developing systems to evaluate project alignment with strategy, optimize resource allocation across projects, and ensure the overall portfolio delivers maximum business value while maintaining acceptable risk levels.</p>
